    <h2>Working Paper Abstract</h2>
    <p>
      This research agenda examines whether environmental, social, and governance (ESG) mandates improve 
      the net financial performance of university endowment funds. Aragon et al. (JFE 2025) document mixed 
      performance effects of ESG integration but do not systematically analyze implementation costs. This 
      gap matters because ESG adoption involves heterogeneous expenditures — data acquisition, specialist 
      staffing, third-party ratings, and reporting — that may erode any performance premium.
    </p>
    <p>
      The proposed project follows a two-phase design. First, a structured survey of a cross-section 
      of university endowments quantifies ESG implementation costs. Second, these cost data are merged 
      with publicly available performance data to construct a cost-effectiveness framework. The primary 
      output is a working paper offering evidence-based guidance for endowment fiduciaries on the net 
      value of ESG integration.
    </p>

